Seattle Cultural Spaces


For this assignment, I decided to re-use the cultural spaces dataset that I used for previous homeworks. As I worked on this assignment, I had the idea of making a small tool to help people trying to locate cultural spaces in their area and find information about them at a glance. The final result is a multilayered map using Folium with three toggle-able layers--a heatmap showing the density of cultural spaces in geographic space, an interactive cluster mark point layer with popups, and a standard mark point layer with popups on mouse-click. The popups display the name of the space, its generalized stability ('Unstable', 'Average', 'Stable'), and available parking. Also included in the map is a Geocode plugin, which allows the user to enter an address, zip code, or even establishment name of their choosing. When a place is selected, the map pans over to the point, allowing users to easily view nearby cultural spaces. In a place like Seattle, it is important to know the parking situation, so I modified the mark point icons to be a car if parking was available and a walking pedestrian if it is unavailable. The colors chosen for these points are also very different to further distinguish the two--orange for available parking, blue for no available parking. Since these icons weren't viewable until way zoomed in, I believed the individual point map to be necessary as an option, as users wouldn't have to interact with the map as much to receive quick answers regarding parking. Furthermore, the heatmap helps further encode the density of the spaces in combination with both the invididual and clustered points. In my mind, this tool could help people who are looking to become more involved in their community and find desired information about these spaces easily.
